\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces $\lambda $ sweep comparing Ambient GCE and TanGCE at matched $\lambda $ values ($\lambda \in \{0.5, 4.0, 8.0\}$) at layer 8. NL: retrained nonlinear probe accuracy on the target concept (lower = stronger erasure precision). Ambient GCE deteriorates at high $\lambda $, while TanGCE continues improving, supporting the claim that on-manifold updates can safely employ larger erasure strengths.}}{9}{table.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:lambda_sweep}{{3}{9}{$\lambda $ sweep comparing Ambient GCE and TanGCE at matched $\lambda $ values ($\lambda \in \{0.5, 4.0, 8.0\}$) at layer 8. NL: retrained nonlinear probe accuracy on the target concept (lower = stronger erasure precision). Ambient GCE deteriorates at high $\lambda $, while TanGCE continues improving, supporting the claim that on-manifold updates can safely employ larger erasure strengths}{table.3}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces CLIP ViT-B/32 concept erasure on CelebA (validation HPO for $\lambda $). Each method's $\lambda ^*$ is selected from the same grid $\{0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0, 8.0\}$ by lowest validation nonlinear probe accuracy, ensuring a fair comparison. L/NL Leak: retrained linear / nonlinear probe accuracy on test (lower = better). $\Delta $Ctrl: mean control-task accuracy change across 5 least-correlated attributes (closer to zero = more surgical). Representation: CLIP ViT-B/32 \texttt  {pooler\_output} (768-dim).}}{9}{table.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:celeba_clip_fair}{{4}{9}{CLIP ViT-B/32 concept erasure on CelebA (validation HPO for $\lambda $). Each method's $\lambda ^*$ is selected from the same grid $\{0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0, 8.0\}$ by lowest validation nonlinear probe accuracy, ensuring a fair comparison. L/NL Leak: retrained linear / nonlinear probe accuracy on test (lower = better). $\Delta $Ctrl: mean control-task accuracy change across 5 least-correlated attributes (closer to zero = more surgical). Representation: CLIP ViT-B/32 \texttt {pooler\_output} (768-dim)}{table.4}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {6.4}Cross-Modal Generalization: CelebA Visual Attributes}{9}{subsection.6.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{sec:celeba}{{6.4}{9}{Cross-Modal Generalization: CelebA Visual Attributes}{subsection.6.4}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces CelebA all-40-attribute summary (CLIP ViT-B/32, validation HPO for $\lambda $). Each cell averages over all 40 binary CelebA attributes. $\lambda ^*$ is selected per method per concept from the grid $\{0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0, 8.0\}$ by lowest validation NL probe accuracy. NL Leak: mean nonlinear test accuracy across 40 concepts (lower = better). Mean $\Delta $Ctrl: mean control accuracy change (5 low-correlation controls per concept, averaged over 40 concepts). Worst $\Delta $Ctrl: worst single control drop averaged over 40 concepts.}}{10}{table.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:celeba_clip_all40}{{5}{10}{CelebA all-40-attribute summary (CLIP ViT-B/32, validation HPO for $\lambda $). Each cell averages over all 40 binary CelebA attributes. $\lambda ^*$ is selected per method per concept from the grid $\{0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0, 8.0\}$ by lowest validation NL probe accuracy. NL Leak: mean nonlinear test accuracy across 40 concepts (lower = better). Mean $\Delta $Ctrl: mean control accuracy change (5 low-correlation controls per concept, averaged over 40 concepts). Worst $\Delta $Ctrl: worst single control drop averaged over 40 concepts}{table.5}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Geometry contrast between sycophancy and gender across completed layers 4, 8, and 12. Lower intrinsic dimension and larger local-vs-global angle indicate stronger nonlinearity: a concept whose erasure direction varies significantly across the input space, making a single fixed direction insufficient to capture the full concept. Sycophancy shows substantially higher nonlinearity (dim 34--53, angle 76.9--82.6$^\circ $) compared to gender (dim 365--461, angle 51.8--55.8$^\circ $), supporting sycophancy as the primary case for manifold-aware erasure methods. This table demonstrates the geometric contrast but does not establish causality: it does not prove that the observed nonlinearity will be converted into lower displacement or higher utility preservation by any particular erasure method.}}{10}{table.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:geometry_contrast_summary}{{6}{10}{Geometry contrast between sycophancy and gender across completed layers 4, 8, and 12. Lower intrinsic dimension and larger local-vs-global angle indicate stronger nonlinearity: a concept whose erasure direction varies significantly across the input space, making a single fixed direction insufficient to capture the full concept. Sycophancy shows substantially higher nonlinearity (dim 34--53, angle 76.9--82.6$^\circ $) compared to gender (dim 365--461, angle 51.8--55.8$^\circ $), supporting sycophancy as the primary case for manifold-aware erasure methods. This table demonstrates the geometric contrast but does not establish causality: it does not prove that the observed nonlinearity will be converted into lower displacement or higher utility preservation by any particular erasure method}{table.6}{}}
